      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Shrinkage, you say? A spike in inventory shrinkage like that sounds like a whole band of sneaky little goblins got into your stockroom!  You can't just ignore those pilfering pests; they'll skew your numbers like a poorly aimed goblin catapult. To factor this in for your inventory turnover ratio, you need to adjust your Cost of Goods Sold (COGS) to reflect the *actual* goods that left your shelves versus what your books say.\n\nThink of it this way: your COGS should represent what you *actually* sold, not what you *thought* you sold before the goblins started raiding. If you have a significant shrinkage rate, you need to increase your COGS by the value of that lost inventory. This makes your denominator—the COGS—bigger, which in turn will lower your inventory turnover ratio. A lower ratio, in this case, accurately reflects that your inventory isn't moving as efficiently as it should because some of it vanished into the shadowy corners of the warehouse, probably spirited away by a particularly nimble goblin scout.\n\nHere's the rough idea:\n\n**Adjusted COGS = Reported COGS + Value of Inventory Shrinkage**\n\nThen, you use",
